This is the shared type/constant definition point for steno's editor model, plus the module's public API surface тАФ the three submodules (`interpret`, `movement`, `serialize`) each implement one leg of the pipeline described in the module doc comment, and this file re-exports their entry points (`interpret`, `movement_events`, `serialize`/`escape_text`) as the crate's editor API. A fourth submodule, `sim`, is declared but not re-exported (`mod sim;` with no `pub use`) тАФ it's internal, presumably a test/simulation harness reachable only via `crate::editor::sim` from within the crate.

Core types defined here and used throughout the submodules: `KeyName` (the special keys an editor recognizes тАФ Up/Down/Left/Right/Home/End/BackSpace/Tab/Enter тАФ with `.name()` giving the literal string Plover uses inside a `{#...}` group, e.g. `"BackSpace"`), `Event` (the keystroke IR: `Text(String)`, `Key { key, n }` for a repeated special key, and `Mark(u32)` which records a cursor position `%n` without typing anything тАФ `serialize` and `interpret` both depend on this three-variant shape), `Behaviors` (the profile knobs: `auto_close`, `type_over`, `auto_indent`, `indent_unit`), and `EditorState` (interpret's output: final `buffer`, final cursor `rest`, and optional `target` = where `%0` landed).

Three `Behaviors` presets are the documented "profiles" тАФ `PLAIN` (all off), `SMART` (auto_close + type_over, no auto_indent), `SMART_INDENT` (all on) тАФ and `INDENT_UNIT` is the shared default of four spaces. Tests elsewhere assert `interpret(emit(t, B), B)` round-trips for each of these three profiles; adding a new `Behaviors` field means auditing `interpret.rs` and `movement.rs` for where it must be threaded through, since nothing here enforces that.

Four private helpers are shared logic used by the submodules, not just local details: `auto_close_of(ch) -> Option<char>` maps an opener to its auto-inserted closer (only `(`, `[`, `{` тАФ quotes are handled separately since they're symmetric), `is_auto_close` / `is_quote` classify characters for type-over logic, and `ends_with_opener(s: &str) -> bool` decides whether a line's trailing character should trigger deeper indentation on the next line. Changing which characters count as openers/closers/quotes here changes behavior in `interpret.rs` silently, since those functions aren't re-exported or visible at the call sites without following the `mod` path.